    "summary": "The Schmalkaldic War (1546–1547 AD) was the military conflict between Holy Roman Emperor [[event:2497|Charles V]] and the Schmalkaldic League — a defensive alliance of Protestant German princes and cities formed in 1531 to protect Lutheranism against imperial suppression. Charles achieved a stunning victory at the Battle of Mühlberg (April 1547), where imperial forces surprised and routed the Protestant army, capturing the two leading Protestant princes (Elector John Frederick of Saxony and Landgrave Philip of Hesse) and appearing to crush the Protestant cause in Germany. The Augsburg Interim (1548), an imperial religious settlement, attempted to impose a modified Catholicism on Protestant territories while awaiting a general church council's resolution.\n\nDespite his military victory, Charles ultimately failed to roll back the Reformation. The Protestant princes refused to accept the Augsburg Interim, the Council of Trent was moving in an exclusively Catholic direction, and the political alliance between Protestant princes and Catholic France (which preferred a divided Germany to a strong unified empire) proved insurmountable. The subsequent revolt of the princes (1552), supported by Henry II of France, forced Charles to accept the [[event:2493|Peace of Augsburg]] (1555), which formally recognized Lutheranism. The Schmalkaldic War thus illustrates the limits of military success in religious conflicts: winning battles could not compel religious conversion, and the decentralized structure of the Holy Roman Empire meant that enforcing religious uniformity required sustained political will that Charles, stretched thin across a global empire, could not maintain.",
